The Industrial Training Fund (ITF) has graduated 300 youths in Kogi State, trained under its 2018 National Industrial Skills Development Programme (NISDP), aimed at creating jobs and reducing poverty amongst unemployed youths in the country. The youth who were trained at the Industrial Skills Training Centre (ISTC) Lokoja, for a period of three months, were presented start-up packs and certificates to enable them establish their trades. The Director General of ITF, Joseph Ari, at the graduation said about 11,000 persons were trained in the phase nationwide in various trades namely: welding and fabrication, tiling, plaster of paris (POP) as well as photography. Ari who was represented by a deputy director at ITF, Atiku Muhammed said, “Owing to our desire to fill the skills gaps identified by the ITF/NIDO Survey, our target this year is to vigorously work to equip Nigerians with lifelong skills in the agriculture, construction, transport and services sectors that were identified by the survey to have great potential for job creation.” The Training Manager, Industrial Skills Training Centre in Lokoja, Ibrahim Umar, urged governments to invest vigorously in training the youth, while appealing to corporate organizations and philanthropists to adopt the ITF model. ITF graduates 30 youths in Kogi ITF trains 4000 unemployed youths on vocational skills in Bauchi ... Targets 11,000 youths in 2017 skills development programme Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin